What is the worst that can happen?<br>
<br>
The reactors start “Clean” for both the launch and landing burn. The fuel is uranium235, a natural, mildly radioactive, mineral that exits in nature in vast quantities!<br>
<br>
It has already been stated that the amount of energy that a Liberty ship launch would take would require the complete fissioning of around 10Lbs of Uranium. This means that each liberty ship burn would produce 10 Lbs of fission fragments (roughly). Just over a pound per engine!<br>
<br>
For a successful burn NONE of this would be released into the environment. The worst-case scenarios (in terms of fallout) I would imagine would be for the complete destruction of the light-bulb containment vessels on all 7 engines either near the end of the boost phase but where orbital velocity had not been achieved., or a similarly catastrophic accident occurring at the end of the descent stage just prior to landing.<br>
<br>
Both of these scenarios can be mitigated to reduce the possible contamination.<br>
<br>
10Lbs is about a large handful (I admit I wouldn’t want to pick it up mind) it is the amount of fallout that you would get from a single small bomb. <br>
<br>
Even under conditions of catastrophic failure a GCNR rocket would produce only a tiny percentage of the fallout that would arise from a routine Orion launch, And I (at any rate) have no problem with Orion launches.<br>
<br>
An explosion in the upper atmosphere would disperse the gaseous fission products widely and they would probably remain there for many years before falling to earth. By which time a lot of the nastier stuff would have decayed away. A landing crash would be messier but it would also be more localised and, as I have said, it would only be equivalent to a small bomb.<br>
<br>
We would not be launching or landing atomic rockets in city centres! A launch site in mid pacific would make the most sense. Especially one of those islands that has already been nuked to bits, even the worst accident won’t make it any worse than it already is.<br>
<br>
The risks to the general population from even the worst atomic rocket accident are TINY, Thousands of people die every year on a regular basis as part of the cost of civil aviation. And before anybody says that those people chose to fly, try to remember the towns and cities that planes crash on!<br>
<br>
Hundreds of thousands die every year in motor accidents on a routine basis as a part of the cost of accessible personal transport.<br>
<br>
Even if a atomic rocket crashed in the middle of a city, the number of people who would die, specifically, from the effects of the fallout would be small compared with the routine daily casualties from “conventional” transports systems (There would, of course, be heavy casualties from such an accident, but mainly from the fact that a bloody great rocket had crashed in the city centre! Not specifically because it was an atomic one)<br>
<br>
Viva la GCNR<br>
<br>
