<br>
You have to assume a total inability to do ANYTHING. That is what I could not get the &quot;designer&quot; to accept. One entirely reasonable failure mode is a complete loss of electrical power - caused by any of a zillion things. You must always - in good practice - accept that the system may be unmanageable. <br>
<br>
A fuel pump can rip itself apart - causing catastrophic damage - and there is NOTHING that can &quot;safe&quot; the rocket - by the crew or by ground control.<br>
<br>
In any event, any active (or passive) safing mechanism would be unavailable during a major systems failure - or be a source of risk themselves. (Passive protective are very much prone to this problem. )<br>
<br>
Every time I mentioned a failure mode, the &quot;designer&quot; would propose an ever more elaborate -and failure prone - Rube Goldberg workaround.<br>
<br>
I kept trying to emphasize that I was not trying to promote a specific laundry list of accident scenarios, each of which he proposed a &quot;fix&quot;. I tried (unsuccessfully, so I quit) to convey that there are zillions of potential failures that ANY booster can suffer (and the added ones specific to atomic engines) and that it is GENERICALLY unwise to shoot a critical reactor thru the biosphere.<br>
<br>
On top of that, the specific design details of his engine are bizarre and would take some strange physics and engineering to rectify.<br>
<br>
yale<br>
