<br>
What would the inclusion of a &quot;Deadman&quot; system imply fer a rocket/booster/spacecraft..?<br>
<br>
That is, a purely mechanical system that would seal the reactor (entire spacecraft..?) off, in the event of a pressure/power failure..<br>
<br>
Something designed to kick in and seal off the system iff'n every other controlling system fails..a process that loss of computer and power and hydraulics would not effect..?<br>
<br>
This could be implemented with a crew escape system..or with a mind towards &quot;avoid the fallout and sacrifice the few to preserve the many&quot; viewpoint...<br>
<br>
In essence, turn the failed craft into a heavily sealed and shielded container that, to the best of our ability, is impervious to the rigors of re-entry and impact...<br>
<br>
I don't see this as being particularly difficult to achieve, considering our current level of engineering and technology...tho, the added weight of a proper shielding system might be prohibitive to launch capability, atm...<br>
<br>
