<br>
I accept that we cannot guarantee absolute safety for anything. (Indeed, I have always taken it for granted)<br>
<br>
Absolute safety is a myth that only exists in LA courtrooms (And, unfortunately increasingly in London ones! <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START >: --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/mad.gif ALT=">:"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> ).<br>
<br>
This is my point<br>
<br>
ANY launch system capable of putting 1000 tons in orbit in one go has the capability to do a lot of damage if it goes wrong.<br>
<br>
The argument is how much damage, whether one sort of damage is worse than another sort and whether the benefit is worth the risk.<br>
<br>
A 40,000-ton super-sea-dragon would do a lot of damage if it crashed in a city centre as well. Indeed I wouldn’t be surprised if it killed a lot more people than a GCNR crash, even in the long term.<br>
<br>
Are we saying that being blown to bits or burned to death is OK but radiation sickness is not?<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Payloads of this size are not going to be routine, as I said earlier Atomic launches should be kept for those special moments when there is no realistic alternative.<br>
<br>
I would love to see a SSTO that could take off from Heathrow, just like any other plane. I would love to see a space elevator. I don’t regard either of these as competitors to Atomic launches. Indeed such technology is essential to space colonisation. Using Atomic engines for small payloads is like trying to shoehorn a truck engine into a motorcycle. <br>
<br>
I want technology that could make space available to ordinary people. Like the USA was in the 18th and 19th centuries.<br>
<br>
SSTO and Space Elevator are essential to this, but, to my mind, so are Atomic launches. There is no other way of getting large amounts of material into space within any reasonable cost and timescale.<br>
<br>
If we restrict ourselves to using 500 ton rockets to launch stuff 10 tons at a time then space will only ever be available as a broadcasting platform for MTV etc and possibly the odd robotic probe.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :( --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/frown.gif ALT=":("><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Dusty<br>
